\f3\b Johannes Diederik van der Waals
\f4\b0  (1837-1923) died.  
\f0 \uc0\u55356 \u56819 \u55356 \u56817 
\f4  Dutch physicist, was {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1910/waals.html"}}{\fldrslt awarded}} of the 1910 Nobel Prize for Physics for his {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1910/press.html"}}{\fldrslt research}} on the gaseous and liquid states of matter. He was largely self-taught in science and he originally worked as a school teacher. His main work was to develop an equation (the van der Waals equation) that\'97unlike the laws of Charles Boyle and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://todayinsci.com/11/11_12.htm#CharlesJacques"}}{\fldrslt Jacques Charles}}\'97applied to real gases. Since the molecules do have attractive forces and volume (however small), van der Waals introduced into the theory two further constants to take these properties into account. The weak electrostatic {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.the-hindu.com/2000/07/06/stories/08060008.htm"}}{\fldrslt attractive forces}} between molecules and between atoms are called van der Waals forces in his honour. His valuable results enabled {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://todayinsci.com/9/9_20.htm#DewarJames"}}{\fldrslt James Dewar}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://todayinsci.com/9/9_21.htm#KamerlinghOnnesHeike"}}{\fldrslt Heike Kamerlingh-Onnes}} to work out methods of liquefying the permanent gases.\
\
